Comments

Over the time between 1973 and 1990, the popularity of the name was overall more common than the name ‘Ariel’. The name ‘Ariel’ spiked between the years 1989 and 1990 from 1,617 to 5,366 females with the name. The chance of the name ‘Rachel’ was more common than the name ‘Ariel’, due to the simplicity in the name ‘Rachel’. In 2017, the name ‘Rachel’ has almost double number of females than the name ‘Ariel’.

####The Change in proportion in female Ariel baby names The popularity of the name ‘Ariel’ increased in popularity between 1988 and 1990. The movie was released in the 1989 between the year range where it increased drastically. In 1988, the proportion of popularity was higher than usual being 0.0008, but then jumped to 0.0026 in 1990 after the release of the movie. The percentile of change in Ariel names ends up being 1, which results to the 100th percentile. No other girl names had the a bigger difference in proportions than the name ‘Ariel’. The proportion of names besides ‘Ariel’ were higher in comparison to babies with the name, as shown on the plots above. At the year 1989, the proportion of ‘Ariel’ names boomed to almost a proportion of 0.004, but then slowly declined after the year of the movie ‘The little Mermaid’ being released.Then, looking at the data of the exact year 1989, the proportion of the name ‘Ariel’ was on a rapid incline after the movie was released. In comparison to other names besides ‘Ariel’, the proportion trend remainds the same as the years go on, but a slight increase in the beginning of the early 2000s as the popularity of ‘Ariel’ was on a decline.

Adam’s Findings

Comments

From my first graph I found that there were a much higher proportion of names that started with “Ada” than there were babies actually named “Adam”. However this trend changed around 1960, and from about 1960 - 2000 almost all babies with names starting with “Ada” were actually named “Adam”, this trend again changed around 2000 where the proportion of babies named “Adam” began to decline, while the proportion of babies with names starting with “Ada” began to increase rather sharply. From my second set of graphs, I found that there was a spike in popularity of the name Adam from about 1975 - 1985, and then from then until 2017 there has been a steady decline in popularity of the name.

More comments

These percentiles demonstrate the percentage of babies named “Adam” relative to other baby names in each year. The 50th percentile shows that on average, most years recorded around 3.1% of baby names to be “Adam”. The 100th percentile shows that on very rare occasions there were actually years that recorded close to 70% of baby names to be Adam.

Richard’s Findings

####Comments To begin, I had to find the proportions of names that began with “RIC” or my full name “Richard,” so I utilized the left join function to combine the babynames dataset. My name’s popularity compared to when I was born (in 1999) has declined. As seen in the ggplot, the red dots are on a downward slope which indicates that there was a downward decline in popularity. Furthermore, my name is currently not as popular compared to other names that start with the same 3 letters because the blue dots (which indicate the proportion of all names that start with “Ric”) is higher than the red dots which shows that there are a lot of other names that start with “Ric”. If the blue dots and red dots were a lot closer together then my name would be extremely popular among babies whose names started with “Ric”. Lastly, my name was much more popular in my birth year (with 6514 babies named Richard) compared to 2017 which had only 2269 babies named Richard. That was a total difference of 4245 baby names! Further analysis revealed that my name 18 years before my birth year was, again, much more popular. In 1981, the number of babies named Richard amounted to 16972, whereas, my birth year only had 6514 babies named Richard. That was a difference of 10458 baby names, which also emphasizes how drastically unpopular my name is becoming.

Jasmine’s Findings

Initial Comments:

I found that due to an increase of Ariel names after the release of The Little Mermaid, I found an opposing trend with the name, Jasmine. The movie, Aladdin, was released just three short years after The Little Mermaid. In the graphs shown above, we can clearly see that there was a fluctuating deecrease in babies with the name “Jasmine” starting after the early 1990’s becuase as we approach the 2000’s, the name “Jasmine” was becoming less frequently used. There was however, a spike in the 30 year gap before the movie’s release and I would argue that it was due to the publishing of the original book, Aladdin. Once the movie had been released, there was an increase in commonality and led to a decrease in number of babies being named “Jasmine”.
